# Spring Boot Profiles 🎭

## 📖 What are Spring Boot Profiles?

**Spring Boot Profiles** allow you to define different configurations for different environments.

For example, you may need different settings for:

* Development (dev)
* Testing (test)
* Production (prod)

Instead of changing configuration files manually, Spring Boot loads the appropriate profile automatically.

---

# 🎯 Why Use Profiles?

Without Profiles:

❌ Change database URL manually

❌ Change server port manually

❌ Modify API keys repeatedly

❌ Risk of deploying wrong configuration

With Profiles:

✅ Separate configuration for each environment

✅ Easy deployment

✅ Better security

✅ Cleaner code

---

# 🌟 Common Environments

```text
Development (dev)
        │
        ▼
Testing (test)
        │
        ▼
Production (prod)
```

---

# 🏗 Spring Boot Profile Architecture

```text
Application
      │
      ▼
Active Profile
      │
      ▼
Load Configuration
      │
      ├── application-dev.properties
      ├── application-test.properties
      └── application-prod.properties
```

---

# 📄 Default Configuration File

```text
src/main/resources/
        │
        ├── application.properties
        ├── application-dev.properties
        ├── application-test.properties
        └── application-prod.properties
```

---

# 📄 application.properties

Main configuration file.

```properties
spring.application.name=StudentManagement
```

---

# 📄 Development Profile

File:

```text
application-dev.properties
```

Example:

```properties
server.port=8081

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/devdb

spring.datasource.username=root

spring.datasource.password=root
```

---

# 📄 Testing Profile

File:

```text
application-test.properties
```

Example:

```properties
server.port=8082

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/testdb
```

---

# 📄 Production Profile

File:

```text
application-prod.properties
```

Example:

```properties
server.port=8080

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/proddb
```

---

# ⚙ Activate a Profile

Using `application.properties`

```properties
spring.profiles.active=dev
```

Spring Boot loads:

```text
application-dev.properties
```

---

# 🚀 Activate Profile Using Command Line

```bash
java -jar app.jar --spring.profiles.active=prod
```

---

# 🚀 Activate Profile Using Maven

```bash
mvn spring-boot:run -Dspring-boot.run.profiles=dev
```

---

# 🚀 Activate Profile Using Environment Variable

Linux/macOS:

```bash
export SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=prod
```

Windows:

```cmd
set SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=prod
```

---

# 🏷 @Profile Annotation

The `@Profile` annotation allows Spring Beans to load only for a specific profile.

Example:

```java
import org.springframework.context.annotation.*;

@Configuration
@Profile("dev")
public class DevConfig {

}
```

This bean will only load when the **dev** profile is active.

---

# 💻 Multiple Profile Example

```java
@Service
@Profile("dev")
public class DevEmailService {

}
```

```java
@Service
@Profile("prod")
public class ProductionEmailService {

}
```

Spring Boot automatically loads the correct service.

---

# 📊 Profile Loading Order

```text
application.properties
        │
        ▼
Active Profile
        │
        ▼
application-dev.properties
        │
        ▼
Override Default Properties
```

---

# ⚙ YAML Profile Configuration

```yaml
spring:
  profiles:
    active: dev
```

---

# ⚙ Multi-Document YAML Example

```yaml
spring:
  config:
    activate:
      on-profile: dev

server:
  port: 8081

---

spring:
  config:
    activate:
      on-profile: prod

server:
  port: 8080
```

